    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e5196237_3ce78456",
        "filename": "buildbucket/runbuild/runbuild.go",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 148,
      "author": {
        "id": 1001907
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-04-23T18:31:40Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "That\u0027s not how I read the code that consumes build messages; if there\u0027s a parse or validation error then it will log the error but the old build message stays \u0027current\u0027. I\u0027m saying that if an error occurs we also need to retain that fact and somehow indicate that the \u0027final\u0027 build is actually stale (not what the user code actually transmitted). Maybe just keep the error alongside the build?\n\nThis would allow us to distinguish between a build which ended in state X and a build which appears to end in state X, but ACTUALLY wanted to be state Y (which contained some error)",
      "parentUuid": "2b03403b_ecaecbca",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 148,
        "startChar": 21,
        "endLine": 148,
        "endChar": 26
      },
      "revId": "37f262445567f3169ec7deb81b91ba59843ca8f1",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "1c294f1b_6a098ec5",
        "filename": "buildbucket/runbuild/runbuild.go",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 148,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-04-25T01:59:35Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "quote from https://docs.google.com/document/d/1RFeprmxM81fRaR2sjo0HJcIGIfko06ciAvzgFAjjXGQ/edit?ts\u003d5c78900a#\n\n\u003e All build proto messages kitchen reads from logdog logs must be valid, according to proto comments, especially step.proto. If any of them is not valid, the build is considered infra-failed.\n\nI think this is important, otherwise a permissive behavior will lead to flaky behavior (overall build fails if the most recent build message was valid, but if the most recent build message was valid, then the build fails).\n\nThis means, as soon as the executable returns an invalid message, we can fail the entire build and there is no need to compare.\n\ni\u0027ve updated common.proto",
      "parentUuid": "e5196237_3ce78456",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 148,
        "startChar": 21,
